.TH "TEMPORAL.DURATION" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.Duration \- Temporal.Duration
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]Temporal.Duration\f[B]\f[R] object represents a
difference between two time points, which can be used in date/time
arithmetic.
It is fundamentally represented as a combination of years, months,
weeks, days, hours, minutes, seconds, milliseconds, microseconds, and
nanoseconds values.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.SS ISO 8601 duration format
\f[CR]Duration\f[R] objects can be serialized and parsed using the \c
.UR https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601#Durations
ISO 8601 duration format
.UE \c
\ (with some extensions specified by ECMAScript).
The string has the following form (spaces are only for readability and
should not be present in the actual string):
.IP
.EX
±P nY nM nW nD T nH nM nS
.EE
.TP
\f[B]±\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An optional sign character (\f[CR]+\f[R] or \f[CR]\-\f[R]), which
represents positive or negative duration.
Default is positive.
.TP
\f[B]P\f[R]
A literal character \f[CR]P\f[R] or \f[CR]p\f[R] that stands for
\(lqperiod\(rq.
.TP
\f[B]nY\f[R], \f[B]nM\f[R], \f[B]nW\f[R], \f[B]nD\f[R], \f[B]nH\f[R], \f[B]nM\f[R], \f[B]nS\f[R]
A number followed by a literal character, which represents the number of
years (\f[CR]Y\f[R]), months (\f[CR]M\f[R]), weeks (\f[CR]W\f[R]), days
(\f[CR]D\f[R]), hours (\f[CR]H\f[R]), minutes (\f[CR]M\f[R]), or seconds
(\f[CR]S\f[R]), respectively.
All except the last existing component must be an integer.
The last component, if it is a time component (hours, minutes, or
seconds), may have a fractional part of 1 to 9 digits, led by a dot or a
comma, such as \f[CR]PT0.0021S\f[R] or \f[CR]PT1.1H\f[R].
Any zero components may be omitted, but at least one component should be
present (even if it has value zero, in which case the duration is zero).
.TP
\f[B]T\f[R]
A literal character \f[CR]T\f[R] or \f[CR]t\f[R] that separates the date
part from the time part, which should be present if and only if
there\(cqs at least one component after it.
.PP
Here are some examples:
.PP
.TS
tab(@);
lw(14.0n) lw(56.0n).
T{
ISO 8601
T}@T{
Meaning
T}
_
T{
\f[CR]P1Y1M1DT1H1M1.1S\f[R]
T}@T{
1 year, 1 month, 1 day, 1 hour, 1 minute, 1 second, and 100 milliseconds
T}
T{
\f[CR]P40D\f[R]
T}@T{
40 days
T}
T{
\f[CR]P1Y1D\f[R]
T}@T{
1 year and 1 day
T}
T{
\f[CR]P3DT4H59M\f[R]
T}@T{
3 days, 4 hours and 59 minutes
T}
T{
\f[CR]PT2H30M\f[R]
T}@T{
2 hours and 30 minutes
T}
T{
\f[CR]P1M\f[R]
T}@T{
1 month
T}
T{
\f[CR]PT1M\f[R]
T}@T{
1 minute
T}
T{
\f[CR]PT0.0021S\f[R]
T}@T{
2.1 milliseconds (2 milliseconds and 100 microseconds)
T}
T{
\f[CR]PT0S\f[R]
T}@T{
Zero (canonical representation)
T}
T{
\f[CR]P0D\f[R]
T}@T{
Zero
T}
.TE
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] According to the ISO 8601\-1 standard, weeks are not
allowed to appear together with any other units, and durations can only
be positive.
As extensions to the standard, ISO 8601\-2, which Temporal uses, allows
a sign character at the start of the string, and allows combining weeks
with other units.
Therefore, if your duration is serialized to a string like
\f[CR]P3W1D\f[R], \f[CR]+P1M\f[R], or \f[CR]\-P1M\f[R], note that other
programs may not accept it.
.RE
.PP
When serializing, the output respects the stored components as much as
possible, preserving unbalanced components.
However, subsecond components are serialized as a single fractional
second, so their precise values, if unbalanced may be lost.
The plus sign is omitted for positive durations.
The zero duration is always serialized as \f[CR]PT0S\f[R].
.SS Calendar durations
A \f[I]calendar duration\f[R] is one that contains any of the calendar
units: weeks, months, and years.
A non\-calendar duration is portable and can participate in date/time
arithmetic without any calendar information, because they unambiguously
represent a fixed amount of time.
However, a calendar duration is not portable because the number of days
in a month or year depends on the calendar system and the reference time
point.
Therefore, attempting to perform any arithmetic operation on a calendar
durations throws an error because durations don\(cqt keep track of a
calendar themselves.
For example, if we are in May of the Gregorian calendar, then \(lq1
month\(rq is \(lq31 days\(rq, but if we are in April, then \(lq1
month\(rq becomes \(lq30 days\(rq.
To add or subtract calendar durations, you need to add them to dates
instead:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dur1 = Temporal.Duration.from({ years: 1 });
\f[B]const\f[R] dur2 = Temporal.Duration.from({ months: 1 });

dur1.add(dur2); \f[I]// RangeError: for calendar duration arithmetic, use date arithmetic relative to a starting point\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] startingPoint = Temporal.PlainDate.from(\(dq2021\-01\-01\(dq); \f[I]// ISO 8601 calendar\f[R]
startingPoint.add(dur1).add(dur2).since(startingPoint); \f[I]// \(dqP396D\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.PP
Other operations, \f[CR]round()\f[R], \f[CR]total()\f[R], and
\f[CR]compare()\f[R], take a \f[CR]relativeTo\f[R] option to provide the
necessary calendar and reference time information.
This option can be a \f[CR]Temporal.PlainDate\f[R],
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainDateTime\f[R], \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R], or
otherwise an object or string that\(cqs convertible using
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from()\f[R] (if the \f[CR]timeZone\f[R]
option is provided or the string contains time zone annotation) or
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainDate.from()\f[R].
.PP
Note that \f[CR]days\f[R] to \f[CR]hours\f[R] conversion is also
technically ambiguous because the length of a day may vary due to offset
changes, such as daylight saving time.
You can provide a zoned \f[CR]relativeTo\f[R] to account for these
changes; otherwise 24\-hour days are assumed.
.SS Duration balancing
There are many ways to represent the same duration: for example, \(lq1
minute and 30 seconds\(rq and \(lq90 seconds\(rq are equivalent.
However, depending on the context, one representation may be more
appropriate than the other.
Therefore, generally, the \f[CR]Duration\f[R] object preserves the input
values as much as possible, so that when you format it, it will be
displayed as you expect.
.PP
Each component of a duration has its optimal range; hours should be from
0 to 23, minutes from 0 to 59, and so on.
When a component overflows its optimal range, the excess may be
\(lqcarried\(rq into the next larger component.
To carry over, we need to answer the question of \(lqhow many X are in a
Y?\(rq, which is a complicated question for calendar units, so in this
case a calendar is needed.
Also note that by default, \f[CR]days\f[R] are directly carried into
\f[CR]months\f[R]; the weeks unit is only carried into if explicitly
requested.
If we carry as much as possible, the eventual result where all
components are within their optimal range is called a \(lqbalanced\(rq
duration.
Unbalanced durations usually come in the \(lqtop\-heavy\(rq form, where
the largest unit is unbalanced (e.g., \(lq27 hours and 30 minutes\(rq);
other forms, such as \(lq23 hours and 270 minutes\(rq, are rarely seen.
.PP
The \f[CR]round()\f[R] method always balances the duration into the
\(lqtop\-heavy\(rq form, up to the \f[CR]largestUnit\f[R] option.
With a manual \f[CR]largestUnit\f[R] option that\(cqs large enough, you
can fully balance the duration.
Similarly, the \f[CR]add()\f[R] and \f[CR]subtract()\f[R] methods
balance the result duration to the largest unit of the input durations.
.PP
Note that because the ISO 8601 duration format represents subsecond
components as one single fraction number, it is not possible to preserve
unbalanced subsecond components during serialization using the default
format.
For example, \(lq1000 milliseconds\(rq is serialized as
\f[CR]\(dqPT1S\(dq\f[R], and then deserialized as \(lq1 second\(rq.
If you need to preserve the subsecond components\(cq magnitudes, you
need to manually serialize it as a JSON object instead (because by
default the \f[CR]toJSON()\f[R] method serializes the duration in the
ISO 8601 format).
.SS Duration sign
Because a duration is a difference between two time points, it can be
positive, negative, or zero.
For example, if you are displaying event times in relative time, then
negative durations may represent events in the past, and positive
durations for the future.
In our representation using a combination of time components, the sign
is stored within each component: a negative duration always has all
components negative (or zero), and a positive duration always has all
components positive (or zero).
Constructing a duration with components of mixed signs is invalid and
will be rejected by the constructor or the \f[CR]with()\f[R] method.
The \f[CR]add()\f[R] and \f[CR]subtract()\f[R] methods will balance the
result duration to avoid mixed signs.
.SH CONSTRUCTOR
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration()\f[R]
Creates a new \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object by directly supplying
the underlying data.
.SH STATIC METHODS
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.compare()\f[R]
Returns a number (\-1, 0, or 1) indicating whether the first duration is
shorter, equal to, or longer than the second duration.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.from()\f[R]
Creates a new \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object from another
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object, an object with duration properties,
or an ISO 8601 string.
.SH INSTANCE PROPERTIES
These properties are defined on \f[CR]Temporal.Duration.prototype\f[R]
and shared by all \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] instances.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.blank\f[R]
Returns a boolean that is \f[CR]true\f[R] if this duration represents a
zero duration, and \f[CR]false\f[R] otherwise.
Equivalent to \f[CR]duration.sign === 0\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.constructor\f[R]
The constructor function that created the instance object.
For \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] instances, the initial value is the
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration()\f[R] constructor.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.days\f[R]
Returns an integer representing the number of days in the duration.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.hours\f[R]
Returns an integer representing the number of hours in the duration.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.microseconds\f[R]
Returns an integer representing the number of microseconds in the
duration.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.milliseconds\f[R]
Returns an integer representing the number of milliseconds in the
duration.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.minutes\f[R]
Returns an integer representing the number of minutes in the duration.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.months\f[R]
Returns an integer representing the number of months in the duration.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.nanoseconds\f[R]
Returns an integer representing the number of nanoseconds in the
duration.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.seconds\f[R]
Returns an integer representing the number of seconds in the duration.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.sign\f[R]
Returns \f[CR]1\f[R] if this duration is positive, \f[CR]\-1\f[R] if
negative, and \f[CR]0\f[R] if zero.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.weeks\f[R]
Returns an integer representing the number of weeks in the duration.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.years\f[R]
Returns an integer representing the number of years in the duration.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype[Symbol.toStringTag]\f[R]
The initial value of the \f[CR][Symbol.toStringTag]\f[R] property is the
string \f[CR]\(dqTemporal.Duration\(dq\f[R].
This property is used in \f[CR]Object.prototype.toString()\f[R].
.SH INSTANCE METHODS
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.abs()\f[R]
Returns a new \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object with the absolute
value of this duration (all fields keep the same magnitude, but sign
becomes positive).
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.add()\f[R]
Returns a new \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object with the sum of this
duration and a given duration (in a form convertible by
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration.from()\f[R]).
The result is balanced.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.negated()\f[R]
Returns a new \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object with the negated value
of this duration (all fields keep the same magnitude, but sign becomes
reversed).
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.round()\f[R]
Returns a new \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object with the duration
rounded to the given smallest unit and/or balanced to the given largest
unit.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.subtract()\f[R]
Returns a new \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object with the difference
between this duration and a given duration (in a form convertible by
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration.from()\f[R]).
Equivalent to adding the negated value of the other duration.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.toJSON()\f[R]
Returns a string representing this duration in the same ISO 8601 format
as calling \f[CR]toString()\f[R].
Intended to be implicitly called by \f[CR]JSON.stringify()\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.toLocaleString()\f[R]
Returns a string with a language\-sensitive representation of this
duration.
In implementations with \f[CR]Intl.DurationFormat\f[R] API support, this
method delegates to \f[CR]Intl.DurationFormat\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.toString()\f[R]
Returns a string representing this duration in the ISO 8601 format.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.total()\f[R]
Returns a number representing the total duration in the given unit.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.valueOf()\f[R]
Throws a \f[CR]TypeError\f[R], which prevents
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] instances from being implicitly converted
to primitives when used in arithmetic or comparison operations.
.TP
\f[B]Temporal.Duration.prototype.with()\f[R]
Returns a new \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object representing this
duration with some fields replaced by new values.
